46:46.674 --> 46:47.215
At the computer.

46:47.316 --> 46:49.300
In my mind, yeah, at the computer.

46:49.448 --> 47:01.360
In my mind, I'm sitting around a campfire, and I want to tell the story in a certain way that everybody's leaning forward just a little bit, because they don't want to miss what's coming next.

47:03.623 --> 47:10.550
And it's surprising to me how many historians don't understand that.

47:11.350 --> 47:13.853
And so they're flashing forward and back all the time.

47:14.069 --> 47:20.890
and they lose all the tension that is just built into the story if you just tell it as a story.

47:21.376 --> 47:23.619
Armand says yes, you see.

47:23.719 --> 47:41.080
Emory Upton and Henry Halleck and... and other figures I've written about, they're all unique.

47:41.100 --> 47:49.510
But... Meriwether Lewis... Greatest leader of all.

47:49.692 --> 48:00.340
In his own little tiny sphere, there's only a platoon of men, there's 32 men.

48:00.360 --> 48:01.643
Amazing.

48:02.112 --> 48:09.759
But he took them across the continent, and he got them back, and he drew out a little more than they ever thought they had in them to give.

48:11.220 --> 48:15.104
So that's leadership, that's command, too, I think.

48:15.124 --> 48:16.806
And that's exactly right.

48:17.646 --> 48:25.554
A different CO never could have gotten that expedition across the mountains, much less down the Pacific period.

48:25.574 --> 48:26.354
He just couldn't have done it.

48:27.415 --> 48:30.398
You mentioned earlier tonight that instead of doing Clark,

48:30.732 --> 48:37.629
But he is kind of the other presence of the book, isn't he?

48:37.649 --> 48:40.155
Yeah, and I think that's accurate.

48:44.125 --> 48:45.248
Jefferson Pick Lewis.

48:45.532 --> 48:47.055
and told Lewis to pick the crew.

48:48.960 --> 48:59.543
And Lewis did, and he picked as a part of the crew, William Clark, and Clark's commission came down as a lieutenant.

48:59.763 --> 49:01.026
Lewis had promised Clark

49:01.259 --> 49:11.071
I don't think that it was that way.

49:11.111 --> 49:12.953
I don't think it was a cold command.

49:13.073 --> 49:21.102
I think that William Clark and Meriwether Lewis always knew between them that if they ever had a disagreement, Lewis was in command.

49:22.944 --> 49:24.246
They never had a disagreement.

49:25.694 --> 49:27.698
They could not have anticipated that.

49:27.758 --> 49:32.326
Nobody could have anticipated that.

49:32.346 --> 49:33.408
And so we don't know.

49:33.608 --> 49:40.581
But if they had had a disagreement, Lewis was the one in the position to say, this is what we're going to do.

49:40.983 --> 49:46.732
And he also had the presidential commission, which I think is... Because he had a presidential commission in his pocket.

49:46.792 --> 49:53.221
Which we have to take, you know, not to be taken lightly, I don't think.

49:53.562 --> 50:00.652
But you mentioned, again, it's looking at these little things, reading these little journal entries.

50:00.672 --> 50:03.457
Lewis writes back a letter, which is while they're preparing.

50:03.877 --> 50:04.799
And he says, look for this.

50:04.819 --> 50:06.020
Will you go through my desk?

50:07.142 --> 50:07.863
It's in my desk.

50:07.883 --> 50:08.604
It's in my letters.

50:09.125 --> 50:10.467
And so you...

50:10.733 --> 50:22.711
Steve Ambrose says, it's just one little phrase, but how implicit is the trust this man has and the other man to say, go through my private stuff.

50:22.731 --> 50:26.697
I give you permission to look to my desk, to my personal offense.

50:26.778 --> 50:30.443
That tells you something about this kind of symbiotic relationship.

50:30.463 --> 50:31.945
It was a wonderful friendship.

50:32.546 --> 50:36.893
But you figure that out and you develop that into a sort of thing.

50:36.873 --> 50:44.082
which I'm marveling at your craft as a writer, picking that little thing up.

50:44.122 --> 50:46.465
But thanks.

50:47.266 --> 50:54.255
I've been telling my wife, I said, honey, when I'm done.

50:54.395 --> 50:57.859
Who the hell wouldn't enjoy anything like this?

50:57.919 --> 51:00.062
Of course I'm enjoying the hell out of it.

51:00.380 --> 51:17.443
it's especially nice to have people saying that you're doing this and you're doing that and i've been doing this all my life and i've been working at it and i've been trying to be a better storyteller for pushing 40 years now

51:17.693 --> 51:38.852
I have to say I kind of directed us toward that because your scholarship is outstanding, it's magnificent, and you insist on the footnotes and the text as opposed to endnotes.

51:38.872 --> 51:40.273
That's kind of a very traditional scholarly way to do things.

51:40.293 --> 51:46.559
But you're really focusing on the storytelling and not boring the reader.

51:46.579 --> 51:47.500
And it shows.

51:47.520 --> 51:47.700
It shows.

51:47.680 --> 51:49.062
It's wonderful.

51:49.082 --> 51:51.546
History should be accessible.

51:51.706 --> 51:57.614
I think it's the height of arrogance to wait for your colleagues and other professionals.

51:57.634 --> 52:02.181
I think that history not only ought to be accessible, but it is critical.

52:07.008 --> 52:16.962
To know where you've been, you've got to know where you're going.

52:17.330 --> 52:24.656
And you cannot know where you're at unless you know how you got there.

52:24.776 --> 52:26.458
It's an old navigator's rule.

52:27.178 --> 52:29.140
I've done some sailing.

52:29.160 --> 52:33.544
And you can't figure out where you're at unless you can figure out how you got to where I'm at.

52:33.664 --> 52:35.906
And then where you're going after that.

52:37.968 --> 52:41.090
I don't know that history has a lot to tell us about where we're going after that.

52:42.351 --> 52:46.695
It would be nice to say that

52:46.675 --> 52:53.506
If you'd only study history more, folks, you wouldn't make mistakes, but obviously that's not true.

52:53.526 --> 52:54.788
And it won't help you.

